OpenDoc was created by Apple in 1992 with the idea of shifting productivity=
 from an application-centric model to a document-centric one; there would b=
e different reusable components, like a text editor, a chart maker, an imag=
e editor, etc., that could be dynamically combined to create a document. Mo=
reover, each of those components would be defined by the OpenDoc standard, =
such that different vendors could create and open components built by other=
 vendors on unique operating systems.

The alternative was the increasing Microsoft hegemony in Office application=
s; in that model documents were subservient to the applications that create=
d them, but the implication was that Microsoft dominated the market. The pr=
oblem for Apple and its partners, though, was not only that Microsoft had s=
ignificantly more market share, particularly in enterprises that actually n=
eeded word processors, spreadsheets, and presentation software, but that th=
e application model was simply a much better approach for the personal comp=
uter era. Given the lack of computing power and lack of connectivity, it ma=
de much more sense to have compatible documents made by common applications=
 than to try and create common documents with compatible components =E2=80=
=94 at least with the level of complexity implicit in OpenDoc.

Fluid struck me as a callback to the OpenDoc idea, but a much more viable o=
ne, given the increased ubiquity of networking, which made it possible to k=
eep various components in sync. What was notable is that it was Microsoft n=
ow pushing that vision, in service of its larger project to own enterprise =
data, particularly since the rise of mobile meant it no longer could count =
on controlling the underlying operating system. Continuing from that Update=
:

The way to think about Teams is that from Microsoft=E2=80=99s perspective i=
